and":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ribbesford, Worcestershire, England":"Ribbesford, Worcestershire, England"},"en":{"1485–1526":"1485–1526","1480–1514":"1480–1514","1501–1523":"1501–1523","–Female":"Deceased","1485–1569":"1485–1569","1504–Female":"1504–Deceased","1526–1587":"1526–1587","1468–1496":"1468–1496","1467–Female":"1467–Deceased","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1514":"1514","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1501":"1501","1467":"1467","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1485":"1485","1496":"1496","about 1495":"about 1495","1 Jan 1504":"1 January 1504","1526":"1526","1504":"1504","Binnerton, Cornwall, England":"Binnerton, Cornwall, England","Drayton, Worcestershire, England":"Drayton, Worcestershire, England","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Ribbesford, Worcestershire, England":"Ribbesford, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Haworth (Yorkshire), probably from Old English <i>haga</i> ‘hedge, enclosure’ + <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’."],"variants":[{"name":"Howarth","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Howarth in Rochdale (Lancashire), possibly from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’. The name may have been confused with   Haworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Amy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Amy Haworth was born in 1485, in Binnerton, Cornwall, England, her father, Christopher Haworth, was 17 and her mother, Lady Helen Hesketh, was 18. She married William Beauchamp in 1520, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They 